\int^\infty_1\frac{1}{x^n}dx:n\in\mathbb{R}_{\geq2}\implies\text{The integral converges.}
\int^\infty_1\frac{1}{x^2}dx\text{ and }\int^\infty_1\frac{1}{x^3}dx\text{.}
\int^\infty_{1/2}\frac{1}{x^2}dx=\int^\infty_{1/2}\frac{1}{x^3}dx<\int^\infty_{1/2}\frac{1}{x^4}dx
\text{The main reason that: }\int^\infty_{1/2}\frac{1}{x^2}dx=\int^\infty_{1/2}\frac{1}{x^3}dx
\text{is because although that }\int^\infty_1\frac{1}{x^2}dx>\int^\infty_1\frac{1}{x^3}dx
\text{remember that }\int^1_{1/2}\frac{1}{x^2}dx<\int^1_{1/2}\frac{1}{x^3}dx\text{.}
\text{So, in this case: }\int^\infty_1\frac{1}{x^2}dx+\int^1_{1/2}\frac{1}{x^2}dx=\int^\infty_1\frac{1}{x^3}dx+\int^1_{1/2}\frac{1}{x^3}dx,
\text{which means that: }\int^\infty_{1/2}\frac{1}{x^2}dx=\int^\infty_{1/2}\frac{1}{x^3}dx
1/x^2 < 1/x^3 < 1/x^4
